  "companies": [],
  "statement": "# Subsets II\n\nReturn every distinct subset when the input may contain duplicate values. Duplicate subsets should appear only once.\n\n## Examples\n\n**Example 1**\n\n```text\nInput: nums = [1,2,2]\nOutput: [[],[1],[2],[1,2],[2,2],[1,2,2]]\n```\n\n**Example 2**\n\n```text\nInput: nums = [0,0]\nOutput: [[],[0],[0,0]]\n```\n\n**Example 3**\n\n```text\nInput: nums = []\nOutput: [[]]\n```\n\n## Constraints\n\n- Input values may repeat.\n- Subset order is ignored.",
  "editorial": "Sort values and skip a duplicate when it would start the same branch at the same recursion depth.",
  "solution_notes": "```python\nclass Solution:\n    def subsetsWithDup(self, nums):\n        nums.sort()\n        out = []\n        def dfs(start, path):\n            out.append(path[:])\n            for i in range(start, len(nums)):\n                if i > start and nums[i] == nums[i - 1]:\n                    continue\n                path.append(nums[i])\n                dfs(i + 1, path)\n                path.pop()\n        dfs(0, [])\n        return out\n```",
  "hints": [
    "Sorting makes duplicate skipping local.",
    "Every recursion state contributes one subset."
  ],
  "starter_code": {
    "python": "class Solution:\n    def subsetsWithDup(self, nums):\n        pass\n"
  },
  "entrypoint": {
    "class_name": "Solution",
    "method_name": "subsetsWithDup"
  },
